<section>
  <title>Chapter 3:  Basic Topology of  <m>\mathbb{R}</m></title>

<p>Last time:  Cauchy sequences are convergent sequences, applications to series and their convergence.  Open sets</p>

<p>This time:  properties of sets of real numbers.</p>

<example>
  <title>The Cantor Set</title>
  <p workspace="8in"></p>
</example>

</section>


<section>
<title>Open Sets</title>

<definition>
  <title>Open Set</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>U \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is called an <term>open set</term> if for every <m>x \in U</m> there is an <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> for which <m>V_{\epsilon}(x_0)  \subset U</m>.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example>
  <title>Open Interval</title>
  <p>The open interval <m>(a,b)</m> is an open set.</p>
  <p workspace="3in"></p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>The Reals</title>
    <p>The set of real numbers is an open set.</p>
  <p workspace="2in"></p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Empty Set</title>
    <p>The empty set is an open set.</p>
  <p workspace="2in"></p>
</example>

</section>

<section>

<example>
  <title>Finite Union of Open Sets</title>
  <p workspace="5in">Any finite union of open sets is open.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Finite Intersection of Open Sets</title>
  <p workspace="5in">Any finite intersection of open sets is open.</p>
</example>

</section>

<section>

<example>
  <title><m>\{1\}</m> is not open</title>
  <p workspace="3in"></p>
</example>


<example>
  <title><m>(a,b]</m> is not open</title>
  <p workspace="3in"></p>
</example>
  

</section>

<section>
<title>Closed Sets</title>


<definition>
  <title>Limit Point</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A point <m>x</m> is a <term>limit point</term> of a set <m>A \subset \mathbb{R}</m> if every <m>\epsilon</m>-neighborhood <m>V_{\epsilon}(x)</m> intersects <m>A</m> at some point other than <m>x</m>.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example>
  <title>Limit Points of the empty set</title>
   <p>The empty set has no limit points.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Limit Points of the set of all reals, <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in">Every real number is a limit point of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Limit Points of the set <m>\{0\}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in">The singleton set has no limit points.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Limit Points of a <m>\{0, 1, 2\}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in">The finite set has no limit points.</p>
</example>



</section>




<section>
<title>Closed Sets</title>


<definition>
  <title>Limit Point</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A point <m>x</m> is a <term>limit point</term> of a set <m>A \subset \mathbb{R}</m> if every <m>\epsilon</m>-neighborhood <m>V_{\epsilon}(x)</m> intersects <m>A</m> at some point other than <m>x</m>.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example>
  <title>Terms of the sequence <m>(a_n)</m> where <m>a_n=n^{-1}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in">The only limit points of this set is <m>a=0</m>.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title><m>\{ x \in \mathbb{Q} \, : \, 0 &lt; x &lt; 1\}</m></title>
   <p workspace="3in">The set of limit points is <m>[0,1] \subset \mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</example>

</section>





<section>
<title>Closed Sets</title>

<theorem>
<statement>
    <p>A point <m>x</m> is a <term>limit point</term> of a set <m>A \subset \mathbb{R}</m> if and only if <m>x=\lim a_n</m> for some sequence <m>(a_n)</m> contained in <m>A</m> with <m>a_n \neq x</m> for all <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>. </p>
  </statement> 
</theorem>

<proof>
<p workspace="8in"></p>
</proof>

<definition>
  <title>Isolated Point</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A point <m>x</m> is an <term>isolated point</term> of a set <m>A \subset \mathbb{R}</m> if it is not a limit point of <m>A</m>.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<definition>
  <title>Closed Set</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>F \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is called a <term>closed set</term> if it contains all its limit points.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

</section>

<section>
<title>Closed Sets</title>

  <definition>
  <title>Closed Set</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>F \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is called a <term>closed set</term> if it contains all its limit points.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example>
  <title>The empty set</title>
   <p>The empty set is closed.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title><m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in"><m>\mathbb{R}</m> is closed</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>The set <m>\{0\}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in">The singleton set is closed.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title>Limit Points of a <m>\{0, 1, 2\}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in">The finite set is closed.</p>
</example>


</section>


<section>
<title>Closed Sets</title>

  <definition>
  <title>Closed Set</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>F \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is called a <term>closed set</term> if it contains all its limit points.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example>
  <title>Terms of the sequence <m>(a_n)</m> where <m>a_n=n^{-1}</m>.</title>
   <p workspace="3in">The set is not closed.</p>
</example>

<example>
  <title><m>\{ x \in \mathbb{Q} \, : \, 0 &lt; x &lt; 1\}</m></title>
   <p workspace="3in">The set is not closed.</p>
</example>
</section>


<section>
  <title>Closure</title>

<definition>
  <statement>
<p>  Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.  If <m>L</m> is the set of limit points of <m>A</m>, then the <term>closure of <m>A</m></term>  is <m>\overline{A} = A \cup L</m>.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>
</section>

<theorem>
  <statement>
    <p>If <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>, then <m>\overline{A}</m> is a closed set.</p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>The set <m>\overline{A}</m> is the smallest closed set that contains <m>A</m>.</p>

</handout>
</section>